e:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The process for assessing capacity could also be refined</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to ensure there is clearer d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ifferentiation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> between a chain’s capacity to create new provision and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">its capacity </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to take</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> on a sponsored academy (which is a more intensive process).</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As a Trust, we are regularly producing a project dashboard and other key </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">management </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">information so </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">at </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">relevant information is readily</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> available.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We are aware of the recent announcement of a Regional Commissioner</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> role for each region of England. It is important that this role represents more than just another layer of accountability, and helps to facilitat</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e the role of high performing Trusts and schools in providing support and improvement solutions to others. This role could potentially add </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a great deal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">both </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in terms of brokering support </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">regionally</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">holding those providing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">such </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">support to account fo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">r outcomes over a reasonable peri</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">od of time. However, it is our view </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the Commissioners</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> should not be responsible for prescribing or validating the specific support provided by outstanding providers, including successful academy chains.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is important</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that Commissioners have a full understanding of individual academy trust, potentially achieved by trusts developing a relationship with a nominated Commissioner rather than managing a range of relationships across regions.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Particular challenges and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">opportunities for primary schools</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Academy status can provide an excellent opportunity for primary schools at all stages of development to take on greater responsibility for their own improvement, often with the support, capacity, and expertise provided by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">an academy chain such as ourselves.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> As explained above, there are many opportunities for academies to access resources and provision such as school to school support, professional development and administration services.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> It is an opportunity for families o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">f schools to agree and affirm their own ‘non-negotiables’; the outcomes of which raise standards.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> For many, particularly those that are severely underperforming, it can represent a fresh start for both the school and its community, and provide a new impetu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s for seeking improvement and achieving reform in partnership with a sponsor.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">One key area where primary schools can potentiall</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">y reap significant benefits is through more efficient</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> financial management and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">greater organis</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ational sustainability. It is our</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> experience that many primary schools still do not have access to the necessary financial and administrati</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ve</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> expertise required to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ensure their sustainability</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in the long term</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> or manage the financial freedoms and responsibilities provided to academies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. As a Trust, we see real merit in providing all </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of our academies </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">with access to qualified school business management expertise at MAT level. It is evident </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to us </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that there is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> currently</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a lack of qualified business managers wit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hin the primary sector</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cces</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s to this expertise is essential in building confidence and enabling more primary schools to thrive as academies. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Deep collaboration between primary schools, such as that provided by an academy chain, can also provide a wide range of opportunities for ta</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">lented leaders and potential leaders to gain a wide range of experience across schools, including in relation to providing school improvement support and coaching and developing other</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> practitioners</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Such opportunities can serve to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">develop </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">leadership</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> skill</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s and capacity and ensure a steady supply of well prepared and experienced leaders for headship post</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in future – overcoming some of the particular succession planning challenges experienced </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">with</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in the primary sector. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cali